 20 August 1383","1364":"1364","about 1364":"about 1364","1416":"1416","Bryn, Lancashire, England":"Bryn, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gerard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Camille, Jean-Pierre, Murielle, Emile, Pascal, Pierre, Agathe, Alain, Aldes, Antoine, Armand.","French (<b>Gérard</b>), Walloon (mainly <b>Gérard</b>), and English (of Norman origin): from the personal name <i>Gérard</i>, <i>Gerard</i> (from Old French <i>Gerart</i>, <i>Girart</i>), composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>gēr</i> ‘spear, lance’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’. As a surname of French origin it is also found in Haiti. Compare   Garrard   and also French   Guerard  , English   Garard  ,   Gerrard  , and   Jarrard  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Gerardi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Vito, Enzo, Gaspare, Luigi, Rocco, Antonio, Canio, Carmine, Filippo, Francesco, Giovanni, Libero.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Gerardo</i> (see   Gerard  ). This surname is also found in southern France.","German and French (mainly Nord): Latinized (humanistic) patronymic from the personal name German   Gerhard  , French <i>Gérard</i> (see   Gerard  ), using the genitive of the Latinized form <i>Gerardus</i>."]},{"name":"Garrison","meanings":["English: from a shortened form of Middle English <i>Gerardson</i>, a patronymic from the personal name   Gerard   + <i>son</i>, or an Anglicized form of its Dutch cognate   Gerritsen  . The English surname is probably in most cases of Flemish or Dutch origin. It was brought to Britain by immigrants from the Low Countries, especially in the 15th and 16th centuries.","Americanized form of Jewish   Gerson   (see   Gershon  ).","Americanized form of Dutch   Gerritsen  ."]},{"name":"Garrard","meanings":["English (London and East Anglia): variant of   Gerard  .","Altered form of French <b>Gérard</b> (see   Gerard  ).","History: This surname (see 2 above) is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."]},{"name":"Geenen","meanings":["Dutch, Flemish, and North German: patronymic from the personal name <i>Geen</i>, a pet form of   Gerard  ."]},{"name":"Gerardo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Francisco, Alberto, Alfredo, Aurelio, Carlos, Jesus, Juan, Norberto, Ramon, Tomas, Ana.  Italian Antonio, Carmine, Dino, Enrico, Marco, Marco Antonio.","Spanish and Italian: from the personal name <i>Gerardo</i> (see   Gerard  )."]},{"name":"Gerald","meanings":["English (of Norman origin); French (<b>Gérald</b>): from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Gerald</i>, <i>Girald</i>, composed of the elements <i>gēr</i> ‘spear, lance’ and <i>wald</i> ‘power, authority’. It was introduced to Britain by the Normans and was fairly common, but less so than   Gerard  , with which it was early confused. In France the much more common variants of this surname are <b>Géraud</b> and   Giraud  ."]},{"name":"Gerrard","meanings":["English: variant of   Gerard  ."]},{"name":"Geron","meanings":["French (<b>Géron</b>): from the personal name <i>Gero</i>, <i>Gerone</i>, a short form of ancient Germanic names formed with the element <i>gār, gēr</i> ‘spear, lance’, as for example <i>Gérard</i> (see   Gerard  ).","Altered form of French <b>Guérin</b> (see   Guerin  ).","English (Lancashire): of Norman origin, from the personal name <i>Geron</i> of ancient Germanic origin, a cognate of 1 above."]},{"name":"Gherardi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Silvio, Alessandro, Angelo, Antonio, Donato, Egidio, Ennio, Enzo, Gildo, Lucio, Luigi, Primo.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of <i>Gherardo</i>, one of themany Italian equivalents of   Gerard  ."]},{"name":"Garard","meanings":["English (London and Buckinghamshire): variant of   Gerard  ."]}]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":18,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Matilda Gerard was born about 1364, in Lancashire, England. She married Sir Thomas Gerard of Bryn before 20 August 1383, in Lancashire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. She died after 7 June 1393, in Lancashire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1364–after 7 June 1393":"umbes 1364–pärast 7. juunit 1393","1360–1416":"1360–1416","1381–1431":"1381–1431","1390–Female":"1390–Surnud","1364–1393":"1364–1393","about 1381":"umbes 1381","about 1390":"umbes 1390","1382":"1382","1393":"1393","1360":"1360","1381":"1381","1390":"1390","around 1390":"1390","after 7 June 1393":"pärast 7. juunit 1393","1431":"1431","before 20 August 1383":"enne 20. augustit 1383","1364":"1364","about 1364":"umbes 1364","1416":"1416","Bryn, Lancashire, England":"Bryn, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1364–after 7 June 1393":"noin 1364–7. kesäkuuta 1393 jälkeen","1360–1416":"1360–1416","1381–1431":"1381–1431","1390–Female":"1390–Kuollut","1364–1393":"1364–1393","about 1381":"noin 1381","about 1390":"noin 1390","1382":"1382","1393":"1393","1360":"1360","1381":"1381","1390":"1390","around 1390":"1390","after 7 June 1393":"7. kesäkuuta 1393 jälkeen","1431":"1431","before 20 August 1383":"ennen vuotta 20. elokuuta 1383","1364":"1364","about 1364":"noin 1364","1416":"1416","Bryn, Lancashire, England":"Bryn, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1364–after 7 June 1393":"environ 1364–après 7 juin 1393","1360–1416":"1360–1416","1381–1431":"1381–1431","1390–Female":"1390–Décédée","1364–1393":"1364–1393","about 1381":"environ 1381","about 1390":"environ 1390","1382":"1382","1393":"1393","1360":"1360","1381":"13